import java.util.* ;
import java.io.*; 
public class Solution {
	public static int calculateScore(ArrayList<String> matchResult, int n) {
		// Write your code here.
		Stack<Integer> stack = new Stack<>();
		for(String s : matchResult){
			if(s.equals("C")){
				stack.pop();
			}
			else if(s.equals("D")){
				stack.push(stack.peek() * 2);
			}
			else if(s.equals("+")){
				int first = stack.pop();
				int second = stack.peek();
				stack.push(first);
				stack.push(first+second);
			}
			else{
				stack.push(Integer.parseInt(s));
			}
		}
		int sum = 0;
		while (!stack.isEmpty()){
			sum+=stack.pop();
		}
		return sum;
		
		
	}
}




logic : 

Every time you score runs, they are written on a paper.

Initially, Track Record [] Nothing is there.

This paper always stores the history of valid scores.

A Stack behaves exactly like this paper because we always work with the latest score.

Why Stack?

Which score do all operations use?

C → Previous score

D → Previous score

+ → Previous two scores

Everything depends on the latest score(s).

A Stack is perfect because

peek()  -> Last score

pop()   -> Remove last score

push()  -> Add new score

Think of the Stack as a Notebook 
Initially - []
Operation 1 - 2  value  - I have  Add score 2. (Notebook [2])
Operation 2 - 3  value  - I have  Add score 3. (Notebook [2,3])
Operation 3 - +  operator -  I have  Add score (2+3) previsou elements. (Notebook [2,3,5])
Operation 4 - D  value -  I have  Double previous score - 5 => 10 . (Notebook [2,3,5,10])
Operation 5 - C value  - Cancel previous score - Remove 10 - (Notebook[2,3,5])

